<br>
Because all things are born capable of love, even if it is buried deep in a dark heart. <br>
<br>
They met in Paineel, the boy and the girl, and they fell in love, though, like many great love affairs, their families and their lives stood in the way of that love. <br>
<br>
She grew up to become a necromancer, though not a very good one, because her heart was not in it. And he grew up to become a shadowknight, which he had the talent for, but not the anger. <br>
<br>
And they both went into the world, and thought of each other. They met when they could, and they shared their love when they could. <br>
<br>
And then one day they discovered the beauty of Stonebrunt Mountains. <br>
<br>
They did not belong there, not in the least; though powerful they were truly cityfolk and not well suited for life in the mountains. But in the peace of Stonebrunt Mountains, they could love each other without reproach, without fear, without hesitation. <br>
<br>
But their kin had caused too much fear for too many. The catfolk of the mountain had long been at war with the lovers' people, and had a bounty on the heads of the heretics. <br>
<br>
And one morning, like so many great love stories, theirs met a tragic end. <br>
<br>
The boy, now a man, went to the river to gather water for cooking. His lover, the girl now a woman, was nearby, singing songs in a tongue that carried the sadness of a race split in half by difference. <br>
<br>
And suddenly, the man no longer heard the singing of his love. <br>
<br>
He found her body, separated from her beautiful face, on the ground at their camp. He cradled that broken body, rocking it, his tears mixing with her red blood, still warm. <br>
<br>
And not long after, the bounty hunters found him. He had just finished burying his lover's body. <br>
<br>
When he saw them, he began to sing, his lover's song, in the language his people spoke before the severing. <br>
<br>
And he fought not with the fear of his god, but with the recklessness of a broken heart. <br>
<br>
He died singing, and knowing that wherever the dead go when they leave this mortal sphere, he would be with his love, and they could love each other. <br>
<br>
Forever. Unconditionally. And without reproach. <br>
<br>
(for broken hearts)<br>
--Lest Ravenfolly<br>
