<br>
Without warning, a scream reverberated off his outer membrane, alerting Cuburt to trouble nearby. It was generally the policy of gelatinous cubes not to become involved in the affairs of others, but being unnaturally curious for a protoplasmic being, he couldn’t help but investigate.<br>
<br>
Round a corner, Cuburt’s cilia sensed a girl in the clutches of a reanimated skeleton. All three of his olfactory organelles detected fear in the little girl’s pheromones, so he began to envelop the skeleton with several pseudopods. As the skeleton realized it was being digested, it released the girl and started struggling to free itself. The girl tottered precariously on a ledge for a few moments, but Cuburt’s flagellum was too slow to catch her. He did manage to snag her dress, but he could feel from the inferior weave of the material that it would not hold.<br>
<br>
Helpless to prevent otherwise, Cuburt listened to the girl plummet into a pool of ravenous piranhas. As his mitochondria sprang into life to process the skeleton’s remains into energy he could use, he thought it prudent to form a protective membrane around the little girl’s dress, which was still entangled in his flagellum. ‘Perhaps someone will want this to remember her by,’ he thought to himself. Cuburt was quite fond of keepsakes and deduced that other beings might share his sentimentality.<br>
<br>
No sooner had he enveloped the dress in its own special vacuole and returned to his assigned area, when he felt the vibrations of footsteps approaching. It was an adult human, male, and wearing size 12 leather boots, judging by the nature of the vibrations. He began pushing the girl’s dress to his surface in order that the human might easily reach it.<br>
<br>
“Aha! There’s the foul thing!” cried the human. A sword cruelly sliced his membrane and his cytoplasm began streaming out. Cuburt desperately tried to show he meant no harm by forming a crude face out of two fire beetle eyes and a pair of rat whiskers, but to no avail.<br>
<br>
As the second sword strike pierced Cuburt’s nucleus, he lamented that he would never be able to engage in mitosis. ‘Capricious fates, would that you’d given me large cute eyes and a furry hide to protect me!’ he mourned. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=isharramoonsong>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 738<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/13/02 7:49:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Cuburt's Demise</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Cuburt desperately tried to show he meant no harm by forming a crude face out of two fire beetle eyes and a pair of rat whiskers, but to no avail.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
