<br>
Despite his age, despite the heaviness in his muscles and the aches in his bones, the cyclops traveled. This was still his world, he thought, and still his world to see.<br>
<br>
He remembered when elves ruled the shoreline, when the Desert of Ro was the Eldarr Forest. When he wandered, often he would stop and become entranced in those memories, illusions covering up the ugly reality that remained. <br>
<br>
Here, I fought the elf-knight Veridyl and won. Here a great dragon laid her eggs, only to find them destroyed by a rival. Here my son died. And here. And here. All my sons are dead, he thinks. But I still remain. <br>
<br>
In the cyclops' pocket, he carried a ring. He knew it was magical, but understood the concept only in the way laypeople understand magic. It holds power. This ring is special, and I don't know why. <br>
<br>
So he carried it. He found the ring on the ground in the Eldarr Forest centuries ago, and kept it because it was pretty. Cyclops are simple creatures and keep very little by way of possessions. <br>
<br>
And though his one enormous eye is still clear and bright, the cyclops is blind to one thing: the ring he carries makes him a hunted creature.<br>
<br>
And so the ancient cyclops wanders, stands hip-deep in the Ocean of Tears, listens to the gulls, and waits for the world to change again. He has seen it change many times. Through one great green eye he has watched history unfold. <br>
<br>
But tomorrow and tomorrow and tomorrow he will be hunted. And he will die for a chip of gold he pocketed from the floor of a forest that no longer exists. And with him will die the memories of a world since past. <br>
<br>
-Lest <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kimayasilverbark>Kimaya Silverbark</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://prod.bsis.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/p/Groups/15/15568/folders/6507/67125button-wolf-pawprint" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Tao Te Bark</span><br>  Posts: 511<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/16/02 4:24:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/p/Groups/15/15568/pages/34736/Kimaya-60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hunter Thoughts</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Quoth Isharra: &quot;This thread is making it very difficult to earn experience anymore....&quot;</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Welcome to Kimaya's world...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Kimaya wasn't hungry.  She had just finished snacking on a juicy piece of fruit, its sweetness still playing about on her tongue.<br>
<br>
She wasn't hunting for food.<br>
<br>
Kimaya wasn't cold.  She was nestled cozily into the folds of the warm scouting cloak she had earned in Katta, her finger gently tracing the neatly embroidered &quot;KS&quot; they had stitched just inside the collar.<br>
<br>
She wasn't hunting for shelter.  Nor did she hunt to protect her own safety.  Once again, she was hunting for the safety of others, and each time she did it she wished it would fix everything so she'd never have to hurt anything ever again.<br>
<br>
She ducked her head as she peered around the corner of the tunnel leading deeper into the kobold warrens.  It wasn't that she was afraid of being ambushed, as most of the bearmen-barking-like-dogs had stopped daring to attack her ages before.  A part of her was hoping that, if they didn't know she was looking, she might catch them doing something natural.<br>
<br>
She didn't.<br>
<br>
Once again, that little stab in her heart deepened as she overheard gutteral growls celebrating a recent kill of a young &quot;tall-header&quot;, and plans to venture back out in the night to assault a newly trained &quot;meowl-walker&quot; scout as it tried to learn its new route.  She paused as she listened.  She wanted them to be good, she wanted them to learn.  More than anything else in the world right then, she wanted them to hunt for food, or for shelter, or even to thin out an overpopulated rank.<br>
<br>
But they didn't.<br>
<br>
They wanted to hunt simply to steal the lives of others, simply to be mean, and she couldn't let them do it.  She stepped from the concealing camouflage and asked them if they'd please do something else instead, but they only attacked in reply.  She kinda knew they would.  Her hammer swung smoothly, and the wounds were clean, the vines holding them still as they turned away to ensure their deaths were as quick as she could possibly make them.  <br>
<br>
Yet with each splintering of bone, something cracked in echo inside her.  With each bruise she crushed, her soul ached more deeply.  She felt their arrogant anger turn to selfish fear, and it made her want to yell at them, MAKE them behave, MAKE them stop hurting people so she didn't have to make them hurt.<br>
<br>
She didn't cry.  No matter how much she wanted to when she had to hunt, she never cried.  Instead she paused over the lifeless bodies, wishing them a safe journey into their next step, searching for any final gifts left behind to do the good they failed to perform in life.  And as she often wished since the day she first had to help squash a bug to keep it from killing Kenyon, she wished she'd never have to hurt anything ever again.  But wishing wasn't making anything true, so with a quick sigh she turned back to helping the world of the living.<br>
<br>
She retrieved a small empty bag, a worn bokken, and a few battered coins.  She gave the bag to a young man training his skills just inside the tunnels, and earmarked the coins to pay for frosting on her next batch of cookies.  The bokken she took with her out into the mountains.  There was a young scout she had to find as it tried to learn a new route, and it probably needed protection. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kimayasilverbark>Kimaya Silverbark</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://prod.bsis.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/p/Groups/15/15568/folders/6507/67125button-wolf-pawprint" BORDER=0> at: 12/17/02 3:18:06 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bakanome>Bakanome</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 536<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/16/02 7:43:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...prey thoughts</span><hr size=1> &quot;Yer never know how yer life turns out, do yer.&quot;<br>
&quot;Nope.&quot;<br>
&quot;Nay.&quot;<br>
The others stayed silent.<br>
<br>
The campfire cracked slowly, showering tiny sparks onto the soggy ground of the plains.  It cast a flickering light on the few figures hunched around it, illuminating each detail of their face, while barely creeping around the edges of their assembled, battered animal skin huts.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yer know.&quot;  The tall one glanced around the group, the scars of the battleworn mounted upon his once youthful cheek as dreadful trophies.  &quot;Long afore yer use tae be out 'ere.  Long afore we were out 'ere, I used ter 'ave a keen interest in a young lass back home.  Back in Halas.  Real beauty, she was, just yer comfy height below yer, big, strong.  Honest.&quot;  The big man sighed, his shoulders consigned to carrying a dreadful weight.  He stared into the floor.  &quot;I miss 'er, yer know.  She prob'ly be marryin' some blader, yer know, warrior, big type, noble.  Rich.  I be hopin' she 'aves an 'appy life, but I can't 'elp but think what we could have 'ad together.&quot;<br>
<br>
A general rumble of consent came from the group.  The stoutest one, a dwarf with an unkempt beard, ragged from years of neglect and glass trimming, nodded solemly.  &quot;We be leavin a lot behind.  We should never have be botherin tryin ter survive out here.  Should havin died.  Better than livin like this.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It's not that bad.  We are living the dream of many a nobleman, you know.  Life on the open road, no one to regulate us, no one to catch us.  We are a law unto ourselves.&quot;  A young elf.  She sounded reasonably upbeat, but her tone betrayed her true feelings.  A melanchony as black as pitch lay poised beneath her jovial speech.  Her fingers lay nervously upon her scimitar hilt, forever poised for inevitable, unending and final combat.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yer naive, lass.  Yer will learn..  Yer will learn, there ain't bein' no freedom 'bout bein a bandit.  Yer live, and yer die by yer sword.&quot;<br>
<br>
A human nodded, another untrimmed beard among the many.  He drew back the tattered rags along his arm to reveal a half foot long scar.  &quot;Last of those bastard rangers did this to me.  They think we bother their animals, or something.  If they weren't trying to kill us so often, those damned animals, we wouldn't fight them so often.  Shortsighted little ranger sh-&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Be quiet and drink yer ale,&quot; the dwarf said sharply.  He narrowed his eyes, the great lines of sleeplessness being a scar of their very own.  &quot;We'll be movin termorow.  Word's been gettin out they know where we be.&quot;  The dwarf picked himself off the ground.  &quot;Expectin yer all to be ready.&quot;<br>
<br>
______________________<br>
<br>
The day had dawned.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hmm, not much here, is there.&quot;<br>
&quot;Nae, tae bandits, they nae look all that rich.&quot;<br>
<br>
A young human, clad from head to toe in banded mail, plodded slowly across the bloodstained earth, the Ghoulbane swung low to his side as he scanned the camp for survivors.<br>
<br>
&quot;Looks like that's all of them.&quot;<br>
&quot;Yep, sure looks that way.&quot;<br>
<br>
The human and his tall female companion fanned out across the camp, checking each body for useful trinkets, weapons, money, anything that might prove worthwhile.  A few knocked out golden teeth.  A fine steel or bronze weapon or two.<br>
<br>
A tall Halasman, his face sadly at ease lay prone, a crimson stain spreading from his belly.  It surrounded a small golden trinket, enveloping it in a blanket of colour.  The human absently picked it up and looked it over.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am findin these bandits, they have plenty of tae gold teeth!&quot;<br>
The paladin waved off the comment.  &quot;Just a second, I'll be right with you!&quot;<br>
<br>
It appeared to be a locket of some sort, tarnished by years of bad weather and abuse.  The chain was ornate though, seemingly having managed to survive the ages.  The main body of the locket was a simple circle, protected by little more than a clasp.  It flicked open with the most miniscule of effort, leaving him wondering why it had even survived at all.  Inside was a portrait.  A picture from what looked like a gnomish kamera, poor quality, almost watercolour.  The face within the picture, spoke volumes.<br>
<br>
The paladin looked over to his companion, still rummaging her way through the bodies.  &quot;Oh..&quot; he whispered.  He held the locket up, his eyes darting between the two women, one of them lost in the past, the other trapped in the present.  A great sadness washed over his heart, and he placed the locket within his backpack.  A silent prayer to the Lord Marr.<br>
<br>
All was done.<br>
<br>
___________________<br>
<br>
The heads of the bandits were to be taken to the Qeynos guards, normally.  They offered a substancial reward, but the paladin had refused to do so.  It would only go to the Temple.  Instead, he labouriously carried the heavy body of the dead Halasman to the bridge crossing into the southern plains.<br>
<br>
The corpse floated off down the river, the blood having long since stopped leaking from his body.  If any other than the paladin were watching, they would have seen his hand closed over his heart.<br>
<br>
The paladin sighed sadly, turning to his companion who sat fishing over the side of the bridge.  Saying nothing more, he merely tapped her on the shoulder, and the pair set off on adventures anew, a locket lighter in weight. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bakanome>Bakanome</A> at: 12/16/02 8:10:48 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gatsuthewarrior>GatsuTheWarrior</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 105<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(12/16/02 9:09:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...prey thoughts</span><hr size=1> Heres the only thought i have to that post. <br>
