<br>
The sun shines high in the sky, not a cloud in sight.  A soft chill breeze in the air occasionally wafts past the protection of the mountain.  Grelch shivered as the breeze rattled the beads he work.  The sun was painful, but it was his duty to stand in protection of the caves from the elves, Iksar, and other creatures that lived near the lake.  The goblin beside him was his friend since childhood, Angroost.  He glanced over at his companion, easily his match in fighting skill, with a bored sigh.<br>
<br>
His shift was almost over.  Despite the boring manotony of the position, Grelch was quietly in anticipation.  Today, his sister would be coming of age.  There would be a great celebration as she was paraded about for all the potential mates.  As her brother, Grelch was expected to help her select her mate.  He had no idea who would be present, but his sister had been giving Angroost the eye quite a bit.  Perhaps he could get the two of them paired up.<br>
<br>
Just one more mark to go before their releif would arrive, and Grelch would be able to go to his sister's side.  Surely this mark would pass even slower than the last did.  Uneventful, painfully bright, boring.<br>
<br>
A chuckle of his companion brought him out of his thought.  Glancing around, he saw what was amusing.  A single frail little elf stood alone not far from the road.  Grelch was never sure with these creatures, but this one looked female to him.  She was busy studying some sort of book, occasionally glancing in the direction of the cave.  Her training could hardly be more then either of the sentrys posted at the mouth of the cave.  Either one of them, Grelch considered, would more than best her in combat.  Together she was no match.  Now his chuckle echoed his companion's.<br>
<br>
The elf was taking her time, occasionally glancing up towards them, or around the nearby hills.  Finally, she got up, closed the book, and stored it in one of her bags.  She casually made her way around the patrol path, until she was beside the mountain of the goblins.  She was getting a bit too close now.  Grelch was about to make a signal to Angroost to attack, when the elf made a motion, and a glowing emanated from her hands.  A similar glowing started to surround Grelch.  He made a motion to charge, but suddenly he felt a weight against his mind, distracting his attention despite his best efforts to fight the grip now holding him.<br>
<br>
That was all the signal Angroost needed.  He charged into battle, shouting a war cry, ready to smash the elf.  Again, a glow from the elf's hands, and a force of magic springs up from the ground, binding his feet in place.<br>
<br>
Grelch watched in horror as his partner was rendered helpless.  Desperately, he tried to fight the grip on his own mind, he could not bear to see his companion just murdered without being able to do anything about it.  The grip on his mind held fast.  Once again, the enchanter turned her attention to Grelch, completely ignoring the other companion.  Rage filled him, trying to lash out at this elf bent on destruction, but his body would not obey, making his rage even worse.<br>
<br>
Out of nowhere a sound.  A barking.  Not in his ears, but in his head.  A barking such as would set your spine a chill, like nothing this worldly.  Grelch's rage turned into panic as the barking got louder, poisoning his minds and breaking down his mental barriors to intrusion, helpless to do anything about it.<br>
<br>
In an effort of will, Grelch tried to fight the force holding his mind captive.  A battle raging inside his head.  A futile effort, yet he seems to be making progress.  His finger moved to his command.  Not much, but it is a start.  Focusing every fiber of his will, Grelch commanded his body to move.<br>
<br>
Then a voice entered his head.  One more powerful than his own will.  An elven voice.  &quot;You are my slave now.  Attack this goblin warrior.  Kill.&quot;  In that moment, all the ground Grelch had gained over his own body was lost.  His limbs betrayed him, his voice acknowledging, &quot;Attacking a goblin warrior, master.&quot;  Unbidden, he charged at his companion, swing after swing contacting the immobilized goblin.<br>
<br>
Desperately, Grelch wanted to call out, &quot;Save yourself.  Kill me if you must, think of my sister.&quot;  But his mouth would only utter battle cries.  Angroost looked shocked, but he is a trained fighter.  As if he heard, or at least understood, he turned the attack on Grelch.  Still, Grelch fought the control.  Tried to force his will back into his own mind.  He was not strong enough, and every time he was close to regaining some control, the barking in his mind loosed his control enough for him to lose it.  All he can do is watch in horror as blow after blow strikes one of the goblins he least wished to hurt.<br>
<br>
Blow after blow landed, both goblins tearing each other up, while the elf just stood in the distance and cackled with glee.  With an exertion of force from the torn up body, Grelch slammed his balled up fists into his friend's head.  Angroost crumbled to the ground lifeless with that blow.  Grelch wanted to scream out in agony, the torment of his companion and sister's possible mate dying at his own hand.<br>
<br>
At that moment, the elf left his mind.  A wave of pain sweeps over him, crumpling him onto the ground.  One of his arms is broken, blood pouring from all over his body, several ribs cracked.  In desperation he tries to crawl to the safety of the cave, and hope another sees his agony and comes to the rescue.  He calls out, &quot;Sister, I tried!  I tried...&quot; a tear welling up in his eye.  Hand over hand, ignore the pain, get help.  Forget everything else.<br>
<br>
A shock runs through his body, tormenting his mind and tearing the last bit of conscousness and life away from him.  Both goblins lay lifeless, crumpled on top of each other, victims of intrusion into their minds.<br>
<br>
Deep in the tunnel, Grelch's sister eagerly awaits her brother's return so she can finish the final preperation for the nights ceremony.  She could hardly contain her excitement, and anticipation.  She knew Angroost would be in the line of prospective mates, and she does not think she would be happy with anybody else.  With her excitement building by the moment, she waited for the mark to pass and her brother and Angroost to return from their shift. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=siava>Siava</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://eqsighost.netfirms.com/Siava/ball47.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Raven</span><br>  Posts: 273<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/10/03 12:38:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=37>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://eqsighost.netfirms.com/Siava/conjure.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...prey thoughts</span><hr size=1> Usha trembled with nervousness as her mother fastened the last tiny button on the dress. Her mother fretted over her, jittery herself, as she tried to calm her daughter's nerves.<br>
<br>
&quot;You look absolutely radiant, Usha.&quot;, she gushed as her daughter made a gown-flaring twirl. &quot;I know you've longed for this day, just as your father and I have. We couldn't be any happier.&quot;<br>
<br>
Usha hugged her mother tightly before sitting down at the mirror to make sure her hair was fixed perfectly. As her mother showered her with advice, Usha's mind drifted to the day she took a liking to her beloved.<br>
<br>
They were in school, which was the home of a village elder. Snath, the class bully, pulled her ponytail with a forceful yank just to see her cry. And cry she did. Hytok, the son of her father's hunting partner, had walked up silently behind Snath and chopped him right on the back of the neck! Snath slumped forward, drooled on his shoe, and started to snore. All of the children cheered and laughed.<br>
<br>
Usha and Hytok were merely playmates before, but that day, she saw him in a different light. They became the best of friends and fell deeper in love with every day that passed thereafter. And today, they were to be married. She couldn't wait to start a family and share a life with him like she had seen her mother do with her own family. What a happy day indeed.<br>
<br>
Usha's younger sister burst in the back door. &quot;Usha, mother, it's time!&quot; she squealed with excitement before zipping back out the door. The bride-to-be peeked out the window to see every villager standing in the street. Then she saw Hytok standing next to her father. He looked so handsome in his tailored suit, and was trembling just as badly as she was,<br>
but he was smiling. With a giggle, Usha announced to her mother that she was ready.<br>
<br>
Hytok's heart stopped for just a moment when he sighted his future wife. Never before had he seen her look so beautiful, so lovely, and he thanked the Gods for bringing her into the world. He had known he loved her from the very first time he met her, and was determined to be the best husband and friend to her one could ever possibly be. She was his life.<br>
<br>
His palms grew slick with sweat as she made that awful, traditional, slow wedding walk towards him. She gazed lovingly at him when she reached his side, her eyes as big and innocent as a doe's. Her lips quivered once, and he thought she was about to cry, but then her eyes rolled back into her head. He thought she was having a panic attack, or perhaps a seizure even, so he grasped her behind the back to lay her down, all the while listening to the gasps and outbursts of concern from the audience. He brought his<br>
hands to her cheeks to straighten her head and cried out with horror as bright red blood smeared her face.<br>
<br>
Hytok heard a faint whistling sound, then saw Usha's father grasp his chest. Screams from the crowd, as well as Hytok, were drowned out by the battle cries of young elves as their arrows rained down on the villagers from the sky. Young and old alike were struck down viciously; their flesh torn away for its rich chocolate taste.<br>
<br>
The elves were like bees as they swarmed the entire village. There was no chance for survival, and Hytok didn't want to survive. He buried his head into Usha's neck and wept bitterly as he held her close and rocked. He didn't want to live if it meant living without her. All the memories of her came crashing over him as he cried harder - the smell of her hair, the way her cheeks dimpled when she smiled, the enjoyment in her eyes when they would go drakeback flying through the forest, the taste of her kisses, the sound of her laughter, promises of the future they had made together. Hytok didn't even flinch when a sword pierced through his back.<br>
<br>
