 <br>
Deep in the halls of a forgotten, befallen place are a horde of memories.<br>
 <br>
Of joy. Green places. The dance of fair elven people, of wine and feast and court.<br>
 <br>
Of a single,pure and god-borne fire that smothered it all from the world. And the bones that remained...still remembering.<br>
 <br>
&quot;Marnek.&quot;,they sing. &quot;Marnek has kept us.&quot;,in words only the dead may hear. <br>
<br>
&quot;For Marnek and the Burning Prince, we remain.&quot;<br>
 <br>
The voices fill the broken halls,a speechless chant that rouses only the broken soul. Burnt bones dance to it,adding the percussion of ancient femur and blackened skull. Corpses sway,in rapture to the eternal words. To the dead,it is peace.<br>
<br>
The living come. Some few can hear enough of the litany to remain,knowing the voice of the damned.<br>
 <br>
The rest do not.<br>
 <br>
Dwarves and living elves,Men and Halfling,Gnome or Iksar. All come to break the bones and scavenge what they might from the end of ages. And die. Or leave. They do not hear. They do not learn.<br>
 <br>
The song rolls on,and the dead resume their dances in the lightless places,the immortal words calling dust to shards. Shards to bones. Bones to body once more.<br>
<br>
&quot;For Marnek and the Burning Prince, we remain.&quot;<br>
